<TEXT>
the four manhattan lawyers chanted shrieked and 
slapped themselves not their usual workday behavior 
but they were on a stage performing wednesday night in a 
festival called serious fun at the usually serious alice tully hall 
the piece by performance artist and choreographer ann carlson 
was called sloss kerr rosenberg amp moore for john chet 
scott and tom the reallife lawyers who star in it 
in the piece a work of performance art ms carlson examines 
the lives of lawyers 
i think this is our 15 minutes of fame said sloss an 
entertainment lawyer 
i never really thought id be appearing at lincoln center 
onstage said moore a corporate lawyer before the big moment 
my god this is really something 
their feet firmly grounded in an invisible box the lawyers do 
dancelike interpretations alternately frenzied fidgeting and 
mellow they call a cab go to the beach ride a roller coaster and 
see their suits smudged by puppies 
at one point each lawyer recites something he learned in 
childhood his address a prayer the months of the year 
ms carlsons life gets equal time when rosenberg points 
accusingly at the audience and yells youre the biggest baby in 
this room 
it happened to me in the second grade it was traumatic ms 
carlson said 
at the end their lawyerishness sort of drops away said ms 
carlson they take rose petals out of their breast pockets sniff 
them and drop them onto the floor they lunge out of their box and 
notice each other 
i have friends in the audience tonight but i was somewhat 
selective about the people i notified said moore some people 
think its kind of strange or weird ive gotten a little bit of 
ribbing but most people are very positive 
the program of works by 10 contemporary dance or performance 
companies also was highlighted by the second hand dance companys 
clackers in which a precision dance trio kicked percussion 
instruments strapped to their derrieres and 3b49 a whimsical 
dance portrayal of a taxi driver and passenger by blondell cummings 
and tom thayer 
the lawyers were discovered in 1985 
ms carlson living near wall street noticed the visual 
climate around me was mostly threepiece suits and briefcases i 
had this dream where these four men in suits had their shoes glued 
to the floor 
she asked kerr a civil litigator and former high school 
classmate from park ridge ill to bring over three lawyer buddies 
to talk about themselves and experiment with dance she also spent 
time at a law firm observing lawyers movements and attitudes 
what evolved was a 9minute work with lawyers who look like 
theyre running around and getting nowhere 
its a very frenetic piece reflective of the way we often 
work said kerr we spend little time in the piece 
communicating with each other 
in a way lawyers have a bad rap sometimes said ms 
carlson the suit a power icon in our culture and the lawyers 
vulnerability is a paradox that has a lot of resonance my 
challenge was to blow the stereotype apart let it explode 
the lawyers have performed at the whitney museum and the central 
park band shell moore once cut short travel in china to perform at 
the brooklyn academy of music kerr convinced his colleagues to do 
an impromptu performance at his wedding 
the piece spawned a series called real people starring 
basketball players fly fishermen mothers and daughters a 
different work featuring blind people was just performed at the 
jacobs pillow festival 
im trying to change the nature of traditional performance 
work ms carlson said im interested in extending performance 
into the public creating something that can empower people 
</TEXT>
