<TEXT>
korean air lines says it will appeal a 50 
million verdict awarded by a jury that ruled a kal crew acted with 
willful misconduct by straying into soviet airspace an action that 
led to the jet being shot down 
all 269 people aboard the jumbo jet including 61 americans 
died sept 1 1983 when the plane was hit by a missile fired by a 
russian military jet 
the sixmember jury awarded 50 million in punitive damages 
wednesday a day after beginning deliberations 
families of a total of 137 victims will share equally in the 
award said lawyer milton sincoff the decision also will allow the 
families to seek actual damages in federal courts 
without the finding of willful misconduct the families would 
have been limited to compensation of 75000 per passenger a 
figure set by international treaty 
kal lawyer george tompkins said after the verdict that the 
evidence doesnt support the jurys finding and that kal will 
appeal 
a kal motion to dismiss the case is pending before us district 
court judge aubrey robinson the airline also could file a motion 
with robinson to set aside the verdict 
tompkins said it was not believable as suggested by lawyers for 
the families during the twoweek civil trial that the crew flew 
for hours over soviet territory and radioed false position reports 
two expert witnesses former pilots testifying for the 
plaintiffs theorized that flight 007 spent several hours in soviet 
airspace after the crew accidentally misprogrammed one or more of 
the planes computerized navigation systems before taking off from 
anchorage alaska 
shortly after takeoff a kal captain on a flight 14 minutes 
behind flight 007 said he spoke by radio with the doomed airliner 
and that the pilots voice was under stress or tension 
testifying on videotape that kal captain said he was under 
the impression something truly out of the ordinary was occurring 
the pilot aboard flight 007 reported experiencing strong head 
winds while the other kal plane did not even though both aircraft 
were flying in the same area 
tompkins said the kal captain on the videotape was a 
disgruntled employee who had sought unsuccessfully to remain a 
pilot past normal retirement 
tompkins said the crew aboard flight 007 radioed a position 
report saying it was on course over the pacific ocean about an hour 
before it was downed 
however tompkins acknowledged that something happened in 
the final hour of flight because some of the planes wreckage was 
recovered in the sea of japan hundreds of miles from flight 007s 
scheduled flight path 
sincoff said the families of the dead passengers feel they 
received a fair measure of justice 
the families said in a statement that many unanswered 
questions still remain about flight 007 
their comment echoes that of judge robinson 
at the start of the trial robinson said there are people in 
the us and soviet governments who know exactly where this plane 
was shot down and how it got there 
due to national security concerns nobody will breathe a word 
about it robinson said speaking out of the presence of the jury 
