<TEXT>
the chairman of the house ways and means 
committee is working to force a compromise on a capitalgains tax 
to prevent his democraticcontrolled panel from endorsing a major 
element of the 1988 republican party platform 
rep dan rostenkowski dill trying to block the cut favored 
by president bush and dissident democrats said wednesday that he 
was offering an everybody wins compromise that stops short of 
changing tax rules 
rostenkowski has made no effort to hide his disdain for any cut 
in capitalgains taxes because 80 percent of the benefits would go 
to those with incomes over 100000 a year 
unless he can force the compromise he faces the likelihood that 
his own committee where democrats have a 2313 majority will 
endorse the republican plank 
ive worked out pretty much what i view as a possible 
compromise where everybody wins rostenkowski told reporters 
after explaining the concept to his committee members 
his plan would allow investors to avoid taxes on as much as half 
the profit from the sale of assets held over the long term it also 
would provide a greater benefit than an adjustment for inflation 
but less than the capitalgains rate cuts recommended by bush and a 
bipartisan majority of rostenkowskis committee 
rostenkowski said he was pleasantly surprised at how receptive 
gop members were some democrats were skeptical about how the 
proposal would affect the budget deficit 
rostenkowskis proposal is based on the same arguments that bush 
advanced in asking a capitalgains cut that it would spur 
investment and create jobs the chairmans plan would benefit most 
assets obtained after july 31 1989 including common stock in us 
corporations timber and commercial buildings 
under the plan 
profits from the sale of an asset owned more than one year 
after that date but less than five would be adjusted to ensure that 
gains caused solely by inflation would not be taxed for example 
if inflation were 4 percent a year for five years 20 percent of 
the profit would avoid tax 
when an asset owned more than five years but less than 10 was 
sold the seller could subtract inflation for the period or if 
more advantageous could avoid tax on 25 percent of the selling 
price 
in the case of property owned more than 10 years the owner 
could subtract inflation or 50 percent of the price for which the 
asset was sold 
a major part of the 1986 tax overhaul was to wipe out a 
longterm tax break for capital gains such income now is taxed at 
the same rate as wages and other income 
bushs plan which drew little democratic support in the ways 
and means committee would cut the maximum tax rate on capital 
gains from 33 percent to 15 percent 
rep ed jenkins dga a member of the committee proposed an 
alternative that in effect would cut the top rate to 196 percent 
for two years then raise it permanently to 28 percent and add an 
inflation adjustment 
that proposal is supported by all 13 republicans and six 
democrats on ways and means and jenkins said wednesday he has the 
votes to win in the house 
heres how the various proposals would work assuming a block of 
stock was bought for 1000 and sold for 10000 five years and one 
day later with inflation of 4 percent a year 
current law would tax the full gain 9000 at a maximum rate 
of 33 percent for a tax of 2970 
simply indexing the system so that inflationcaused gain 
would escape tax would result in 8800 gain and 2904 tax 
rostenkowskis proposal would mean a 7500 taxable profit and 
a 2475 maximum tax 
jenkins amendment which would exclude 30 percent of gain from 
taxes would have a 6300 taxable gain and a top tax of 2079 
