thousands of suspected political opponents in 
ethiopia have been imprisoned for months or even years without 
trial and many have been tortured repeatedly amnesty 
international charged today 
the worldwide human rights organization based in london said 
ethiopia has systematically ignored constitutional and legal 
safeguards for human rights and is among the worst offenders in 
africa in failing to ratify international human rights covenants 
in a 13page report on political imprisonment in the east 
african nation amnesty said some prisoners have been secretly 
condemned to death by a special government committee or vanish 
without explanation while in detention 
methods of torture include electric shocks submersion in water 
and beatings on the soles of the feet the group said 
amnesty said ethiopia has responded to the groups charges with 
either silence or evasion it appealed to president mengistu 
haile mariams marxist government to free prisoners detained for 
their opinions beliefs or ethnic origins who have not used or 
advocated violence 
thousands of political prisoners have been detained for months 
or even years on the orders of the state security service the 
central investigation organ without their cases ever being 
referred to the courts the report said 
following a failed coup attempt in may authorities detained 180 
people mostly military personnel but the government has given no 
information of their whereabouts or legal status it said 
amnesty asked the government to either release the prisoners or 
formally charge and try them 
ethiopias constitution specifies that anyone arrested should be 
produced in court within 48 hours and that no one accused of a 
crime should be considered guilty unless convicted by a court the 
report said 
however in practice these constitutional safeguards have 
been ineffective amnesty said arrests have frequently been 
carried out without a warrant and no political prisoner is known 
have been brought to court and charged within 48 hours 
