<TEXT>
the chairman of the senate agriculture 
committee says the senateapproved 885 million droughtrelief 
package is fair to all farmers who suffer crop and livestock losses 
the most important thing about this bill is that all farmers 
are being treated fairly panel chairman patrick leahy dvt 
said after the measure passed wednesday 
those who suffer a significant loss will receive the same 
payment rate 65 percent of the applicable target price or loan 
rate he said we will not discriminate against any farmer who 
needs help this legislation treats all farmers fairly whether 
they grow wheat corn hay or soybeans 
but the measure passed by voice vote toward the end of a long 
senate business day was considerably more modest than a 
housepassed version that many lawmakers criticized as too 
expensive 
members of the house and senate agriculture committees planned 
to begin negotiations on a compromise version today with the aim 
of completing that work before congress leaves friday on a 
monthlong recess leahys office said 
the senate bill makes farmers eligible for federal aid if they 
have crop losses this year because of drought flooding freezing 
hail high winds or similar severe weather it also provides for 
payments to livestock producers facing droughtrelated feed and 
water shortages for their herds 
but its price tag is about 463 million less than the 
agriculture department has estimated the cost of a rival 
housepassed package 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said winter wheat 
producers and other crop growers will be eligible for highpriority 
attention under provisions of the legislation 
this is not the best bill nor is it the kind of relief winter 
wheat producers and other program crops deserve he said but 
it is far better than the budgetbusting house bill which promised 
federal relief to every crop in america 
the senate also passed by voice vote late wednesday rural 
development legislation designed to promote business investment and 
expansion in small towns in rural america it also is aimed at 
improving schools and health care for residents 
proponents argued that federal assistance was needed because the 
61 million people living in rural areas face higher unemployment 
more hospital closings and higher poverty levels than their urban 
counterparts the rural economy also is more volatile because of 
its dependence on natural resources supporters said 
the centerpiece of the package called the rural partnership 
act is a revolving loan fund program to provide 300 million in 
seed money over five years for new and expanding businesses 
the senates disasterrelief bill provides for different 
eligibility standards for various crops but in all cases producers 
would receive payments designed to cover 65 percent of their lost 
income from crop losses 
in most instances the projected income levels will be based on 
federal crop subsidies or average market prices farmers would have 
received had they not suffered losses 
the house bill required a minimum loss of 35 percent for any 
crop to receive assistance with payments covering 65 percent of 
lost income but unlike the senate bill the house measure called 
for 90 percent payments on crop losses of more than 75 percent 
the senate dropped the higher payment level as a way of cutting 
the overall cost of the assistance package 
farmstate senators objected to a provision in the house bill 
that would prevent spending on drought assistance to exceed the 
amount of agricultural subsidy savings and would have prorated 
relief payments to farmers if necessary 
in general spending on subsidy programs is expected to be lower 
this year because crop prices are higher as a result of smaller 
harvests linked to weather problems 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

