<TEXT>
a fruit picker imprisoned more than 21 years 
after the 1967 poisoning deaths of his seven children filed a 35 
million lawsuit today for being wrongly convicted 
attorneys for 53yearold james richardson of arcadia filed the 
lawsuit in us district court 
richardson was freed last april after a state investigation 
ordered by gov bob martinez found that suppressed evidence and 
perjured testimony was used to convict him 
richardson stood trial only for the pesticide poisoning of his 
oldest child and was sentenced to die in the electric chair the 
sentence was commuted to life in prison when the us supreme court 
struck down the death penalty in 1972 
the lawsuit names the state of florida desoto county former 
state attorney frank schaub and former desoto sheriff frank cline 
roger young one of richardsons attorneys in sarasota said it 
was difficult placing a dollar amount on the time richardson spent 
in prison 
its hard you cant really do it young said he was 
without his family loss of liberty and everything thats 
guaranteed to him by the constitution those things were all 
stripped from him because of the actions of frank schaub 
schaub who retired in january prosecuted the case in 1968 and 
blasted special prosecutor janet reno for concluding that 
richardson probably was wrongfully accused ms reno announced in 
may that the state would not retry richardson whose sentence was 
vacated april 25 
efforts to reach schaub and cline by phone for comment were 
unsuccessful 
the suit seeks to compensate richardson for mental anguish loss 
of the capacity for the enjoyment of life loss of income pain and 
suffering and loss of his liberty and rights as a citizen of the 
united states 
