<TEXT>
a federal judge today said commerce secretary 
robert mosbacher had no right to suspended enforcement of 
regulations to protect endangered sea turtles from drowning in 
shrimpers nets and gave the agency until monday to draft interim 
measures 
us district court judge thomas hogan said he would consider 
making the commerce department enforce regulations requiring 
shrimpers to equip their boats with turtle excluder devices or 
teds if the agency does not submit a plan to protect the sea 
turtles by mondays deadline 
hogans decision followed a twohour hearing on the national 
wildlife federations request for an injunction that would require 
the department to enforce requirements that shrimpers use teds 
mosbacher suspended enforcement of the teds regulations july 24 
after angry shrimpers who contend the devices reduce their catch 
by as much as onethird blockaded shipping channels along the 
texas gulf coast and threatened violence against law officers and 
the coast guard 
hogan said that while he is concerned about the shrimpers 
livelihood he said it is regrettable that shrimpers in other areas 
have learned to use teds but that texas and louisiana shrimpers 
cannot find it possible to use the devices even for a season 
the teds regulations were to take effect may 1 after 17 years 
of debate within congress and the courts but mosbacher limited 
enforcement of the rules to warnings until july 1 
later in the month mosbacher said he had no alternative but to 
enforce the teds regulations prompting the july 2223 protests 
mosbacher has now proposed new regulations requiring shrimpers 
to pull their nets every 105 minutes to keep endangered sea turtles 
from drowning but they have not taken effect 
hogan said mosbachers decision to suspend enforcement of the 
teds rules until the tow regulations take effect was a total 
abrogation of the law to protect sea turtles and appears to fly 
in the face of a congressional mandate 
his actions on july 24 leave them totally unprotected hogan 
said they have been totally abandoned by the secretary 
wildlife attorney jan goldmancarter testified the shrimping 
season in texas and louisiana is at its peak so the turtles are at 
maximum risk of being killed in their nets 
she said we are so close to the edge of extinction on the 
kemps ridley sea turtle 
government attorney michelle kurac said mosbachers decision to 
suspend the teds regulations was justified given the protests and 
the shrimpers vows not to comply with the rules 
