<TEXT>
americas low productivity rate which has 
worried economists for years is not as bad as originally believed 
the labor department said thursday 
the department said that productivity has increased at an 
average annual rate of 18 percent over the last three years up 
from an original estimate of an average increase of 14 percent per 
year 
the 14 percent figure which reflected subpar productivity 
rates in 1987 and 1988 had analysts concerned about the countrys 
economic outlook rising living standards hinge on the ability to 
keep productivity increasing at a healthy rate 
economists had also questioned the bush administrations 
economic outlook which was based on a projection that productivity 
would grow in the years ahead at a 18 percent rate 
michael boskin the presidents chief economic adviser took 
note of the labor department revisions in a statement released by 
his office 
we had been anticipating some upward revision in the 
productivity estimates and were quite pleased that nonfarm 
productivity growth for 198688 was revised to a rate almost 
exactly in line with our current thinking about the economys 
longrun growth potential he said 
the revised figures showed that nonfarm productivity increased 
by 21 percent in 1988 compared to a previous estimate of 15 
percent for 1987 the increase was put at 11 percent up from a 
previous estimate of 08 percent productivity growth in 1986 was 
unchanged at 2 percent 
some private economists however remained sceptical about the 
new figures 
michael evans head of a washington forecasting firm said he 
believed that the government was miscounting total economic output 
as covered by the gross national product he said this had the 
effect of inflating productivity which is defined as total output 
divided by the number of hours worked 
i think the commerce department has committed a serious error 
with their measurment of gnp evans said they have 
artificially raised real growth and this makes productivity look 
better than it is 
</TEXT>
