<TEXT>
michael nash former photo and communications chief 
in paris for the associated press died thursday of cancer he was 
69 
nash former assistant chief of bureau photo editor and chief 
of communications retired in 1985 after 44 years with ap one of 
the longestserving members of its foreign service 
he restored ap newsphoto services in france after world war ii 
ann when photographers used bulky boxlike speed 
graphic cameras and ended as the era of electronic darkrooms and 
computerized photo editing terminals was beginning 
during world war ii nash used a speed graphic to make pictures 
of german v1 rockets falling on london that appeared on front 
pages around the world 
when nash retired he was awarded the city of paris vermeil 
medal for distinguished accomplishment in ones profession 
nash also was decorated by tunisian president habib bourguiba 
for widely published photographs he took in 1952 showing unrest in 
the french colony which became independent four years later 
mike was a rare bird in the early days of the ap picture 
service in europe said harold g buell assistant general 
manager for newsphotos he could shoot pictures he could handle 
the desk and he soon came to provide needed insights into 
networking and development of aps complicated picture system 
nash drove no one harder than himself in doing a firstclass 
job in every respect said paris ap bureau chief harry dunphy 
he trained a generation of photographers and editors 
nash was born aug 6 1919 in london where he joined the ap in 
1942 as a photo editor a few months later he switched to 
photographer 
after the 1944 liberation of paris from german occupation the 
25yearold nash was sent to rebuild the ap photo service on june 
1 1945 the ap resumed delivery of news photos to paris newspapers 
a year later nash returned to active service as a photographer 
and for the next six years worked in europe the middle east and 
africa 
in 1952 nash returned to the photo editors job in paris a 
position he held for 34 years he established aps wirephoto 
network in 1956 
nash developed and trained photographers and editors who covered 
wars and rebellions in indochina north africa the congo vietnam 
the middle east and iran 
in 1978 nash took on additional duties as chief of 
communications in paris 
nash is survived by his wife elsie and their sons max aps 
photo editor in tel aviv and timothy an architect in london 
</TEXT>
