<TEXT>
less than 10 percent of people at high risk for a 
type of infection that can cause pneumonia meningitis and even 
death have ever gotten the vaccine for it and health officials 
thursday urged doctors to do better 
the national centers for disease control said 48 million 
americans are at high risk of pneumococcal infections but a 1985 
study found that not one in 10 of them have ever received the 
vaccine 
the vaccine a onetimeonly shot is recommended for adults 65 
and over and for adults with chronic illnesses such as heart and 
lung disease kidney failure cirrhosis and suppressed immune 
systems 
pneumococcal infections cause 150000 to 570000 cases of 
pneumonia and contribute to an estimated 40000 deaths annually 
the cdc said 
assuming an overall vaccine efficacy of 60 percent an 
estimated 12000 deaths related to pneumococcal disease might be 
prevented annually if only 60 percent of highrisk people were 
vaccinated the cdc said in its weekly report 
the cdc praised a twoyear california state department of health 
services program promoting the use of pneumococcal vaccines local 
health departments received more than 60000 doses and were 
encouraged to provide the vaccine during scheduled autumn 
