<TEXT>
america is better at recalling 
automobiles than it is at warning medical implant recipients of 
defects in their devices the director of a new alert system said 
thursday 
there are people who are dying in this country every year 
because the device they are wearing is malfunctioning and they 
dont know it said donald nichols executive vice president of 
international implant registry 
nichols visited the bionics and transplants display at the 
science museum of minnesota to call attention to his fledgling 
nonprofit service which has been spurned by several large 
manufacturers of medical implant devices 
the registry part of turlock califbased medic alert seeks 
to create a computer data base of implantable devices and notify 
physicians of government warnings or manufacturer recalls the 
physicians would use addresses provided by the registry to contact 
their patients 
although federal regulations require medical device makers to 
report product hazards to the us food and drug administration 
the agency has no direct way to notify hospitals physicians or 
patients of product recalls nichols said manufacturers forward 
the warnings to the medical institutions and doctors who purchased 
the devices he said but patient addresses are often outdated 
nichols estimated that the contact rate in some alert cases is 
as low as 30 percent the registry he said could consistently 
achieve a contact rate of more than 80 percent 
the record overall is not a good one nichols said right 
now in this country we can recall automobiles more quickly than we 
can recall the devices that are in peoples bodies 
in washington dc however a consumer group said the fda was 
negligent and reckless in failing to enforce the notification 
law 
public citizen health research group said fda documents showed 
makers of heart pacemakers wheelchairs and breast implants ignore 
the reporting requirement and that the fda has failed to seek 
prosecution of the companies 
the fda said it disagreed with the assessment and that the group 
had incorrectly interpreted some data in evaluating the public 
health risk 
kent milton of the national highway traffic safety 
administration in washington dc said the notification rate on 
automobile recalls is never below 50 percent 
nichols said the importance of prompt patient warnings was 
underscored in 1985 when a defect in a series of bjorkshiley 
artificial heart valves resulted in about 100 deaths he said the 
registry would have speeded the warnings and possibly saved lives 
a spokeswoman for irving califbased bjorkshiley said the firm 
was checking whether or not this was a problem for them in 1985 
nichols said only a few device manufacturers are interested in 
paying for the service the registry charges an initial fee of 25 
a patient and 10 a patient each subsequent year 
dick reid a spokesman for fridleybased medtronic inc one of 
the largest manufacturers of heart pacemakers said the registry 
would be a costly duplication of a service medtronic already 
provides 
we have our own patient implant registry and we keep it 
updated reid said at least in the pacemaker area we feel it 
tracks 98 percent of the medtronic pacemakers in place in the 
united states 
nichols said medtronic has a good record of notifying customers 
of defects but he said the industry as a whole is weak more than 
11 million people receive medical implants annually and the 
industry produces an array of more than 200 devices 
a spokeswoman for the fda in chicago said the agency is not 
aware of the registry and therefore could not comment on whether 
there is a need for it 
mark wood an account manager in the risk management department 
at st paul companies the largest medical malpractice insurance 
underwriter in the us said there is room for improvement in 
warning patients of implant defects but he said he is not familiar 
with the international implant registry 
having some kind of a standardized system where you could 
track a product to its end user could be helpful wood said 
still in its first year the registry has only 15000 entries 
nichols said it must add 10000 to 12000 entries a year to be 
successful and the first eight months of this year have yielded 
only 3000 additions 
nichols said the registry is planning to appeal directly to 
implant patients to pay for the service its too early to tell if 
that approach will work he said 
</TEXT>
