<TEXT>
a congressional study released thursday said 
cable television charges have risen 29 percent since federal 
regulation ended three years ago several legislators complained 
about inadequacies in the report and one called it virtually 
useless 
the report by the general accounting office an investigative 
arm of the congress was presented to the telecommunications 
subcommittee of the house energy and commerce committee 
shortly afterward sen al gore dtenn issued a statement 
saying the study is badly flawed and virtually useless to 
congress 
gore who has introduced a senate bill to reregulate the cable 
industry and encourage competition called the study results out 
of date and pointed out that the agency had surveyed less than 20 
percent of the industry 
indeed members of the subcommittee itself were critical of the 
report because while it examined rate increases instituted in the 
22 months following deregulation it contained no information about 
cable companies capitalization costs the selling of franchises 
advertising revenue or the industrys financial picture 
the committee chairman rep edward markey dmass asked the 
gao to prepare a second study by next spring addressing a wider 
range of concerns 
there are some things that need to be looked at in a little 
more detail than our study shows conceded john m ols jr 
director of housing and community development issues for the gao 
but he said the survey released thursday was patterned on 
instructions from the subcommittee 
as for the gao data ols said we stand behind those figures 
from a statistical standpoint he said the survey of 1950 of the 
nations approximately 9000 cable operators was roughly a 
national sample we took really more than we had to 
but rep rick boucher dva said he suspected that the 25 
percent of cable operators that did not respond to the survey had 
imposed substantially higher rate increases than those that did 
respond 
the gao report found that the average monthly rate for the least 
expensive basic cable service increased 29 percent from december 
1986 when government regulations were lifted to october 1988 the 
average basic fee rose from 1123 to 1448 during the study 
period the gao said 
despite the stiff increase for basic service the gao said the 
average subscribers monthly bill rose a smaller 14 percent from 
2158 to 2468 
industry representatives told the panel that customers are 
getting a better value for their money now than in 1986 because the 
quality of cable offerings has improved and the average number of 
channels offered by cable systems has risen from 24 to 30 
cable companies channeled 246 million in 1986 292 million in 
1987 and 417 million in 1988 into upgrading equipment and adding 
channels said james p mooney president and chief executive 
officer of the national cable television association 
under deregulation the federal communications commission 
allowed cable television operators who since 1972 had to receive 
permission from local authorities to raise prices for basic 
service to set their own rates 
