the us court of international trade imposed 
a record 34 million fine thursday against a south korean steel 
manufacturer for alleged customsfraud violations the justice 
deparment said 
the department said the fine against daewoo corp and its us 
subsidiary daewoo international america corp essentially 
reflects a settlement agreement negotiated by the government and 
the company 
the judgment entered by the trade court in new york is a 
result of civil lawsuit charging customslaw fraud in connection 
with steel imports from 1980 through 1982 the civil case was filed 
after the company pleaded guilty in 1985 to criminal violations in 
connection with nine steel importations 
the lawsuit accused the company of routinely giving the us 
customs service false declarations of the price of steel it was 
shipping to the united states to avoid paying duties for 
dumping the product at low prices 
the civil investigation found about 800 alleged violations in 
connection with 235 importations of steel the department said 
the largest customs penalty before thursdays fine was a 25 
million fine imposed in 1982 on volkswagen usa 
