<TEXT>
botswanas president was named a cowinner 
of the 1989 africa prize for leadership for having prevented famine 
in his nation during the 19811987 drought 
president quett kj masire shares the prize with dr bernard 
ledea ouedraogo of burkina faso ouedraogo an antihunger 
activist heads grassroots organizations that involve more than 
500000 people in nine countries 
the new yorkbased hunger project which awards the prize said 
not a single person died of starvation during botswanas sevenyear 
drought the worst in that countrys history 
during the seven years masire actually managed to reduce hunger 
in his country the project said 
before the drought 25 percent of botswanas children were below 
average weight by 1987 the figure had fallen to less than 15 
percent 
infant mortality in botswana now at 72 deaths for every 1000 
live births is the lowest in subsaharan africa 
ouedraogo has organized more than 500000 peasants to end hunger 
through selfreliance and development 
he heads the naam movement and programs that teach peasant 
farmers agricultural techniques reforestation methods road 
building and how to improve health care they also give villagers 
literacy training 
the program is active in burkina faso chad gambia 
guineabissau mali mauritania niger senegal and togo 
the 100000 prize is to promote the winners work 
the africa prize for leadership award was instituted two years 
ago by the nonprofit organization about 54 million volunteers 
and staff in 152 nations are helping the hunger project try to 
abolish hunger worldwide organizers said 
last year president robert g mugabe of zimbabwe won the prize 
while in the previous year the award went to president abdou diouf 
of senegal and professor thomas r odhiambo of kenya a specialist 
in insect studies 
