<TEXT>
the house voted thursday to make permanent the 
ban on cigarette smoking on airline flights lasting two hours or 
less a restriction the tobacco industry fought two years ago but 
now sees as preferable to threatened broader limits 
the measure would prevent the current ban which covers four out 
of five domestic us flights from expiring as scheduled in april 
in a victory for the cigarette industry however antismoking 
forces were blocked from adding language that would have spread the 
prohibition to all domestic flights 
this is probably the most popular bill weve passed around 
here in two years said rep richard durbin dill sponsor of 
both the existing and the new restrictions 
the extended prohibition was contained in an 119 billion 
transportation bill for fiscal 1990 that the house passed 36650 
the measure will next be considered by the senate where an effort 
is expected to broaden the smoking restrictions 
the key fight on the smoking question occurred wednesday when 
lawmakers adopted the ban on a 259169 vote that vote was a 
procedural one that included other issues but the cigarette 
restrictions dominated the days debate 
when congress enacted the initial ban two years ago the tobacco 
industry actively fought the proposal with claims that growers 
would lose business and assertions that smoking was a health hazard 
were unproven the house approved the ban in 1987 by a slim 198193 
margin 
this year after early votes by house committees indicated that 
lawmakers were not receptive to completely killing the 
restrictions the tobacco lobby decided it could live with a 
permanent extension of the ban on twohour flights the industry 
reasoned that making the restriction permanent would eliminate 
opportunities for the ban to be expanded every time it expired 
they counted noses durbin said of the tobacco industrys 
tactics 
asked about the cigarette lobbys decision to do little to block 
the permanent extension of the ban rep walter jones dnc 
whose district relies heavily on tobacco growing said wednesday 
this is the best compromise we can get 
the bill limits spending to 12 million for the program that 
pays subsidies to airlines serving small communities about 31 
million is being spent this year on the program a tiny portion of 
the transportation budget that bigcity lawmakers say is largely a 
waste of money 
the measure also provides 73 billion for the federal aviation 
administration 960 million more than this year 29 billion for 
the coast guard about 100 million more than 1989 32 billion 
for mass transit and 615 million for amtrak which got 584 
million this year 
the bill provides 119 billion in new spending but also allows 
an additional 153 billion to be spent from revenues from various 
user fees 
