<TEXT>
a federal judge thursday ordered a us art 
dealer to return to the greek orthodox church of cyprus four 6th 
century mosaics purchased for 11 million last summer in 
switzerland 
us district judge james e noland said in his ruling that peg 
goldberg of suburban indianapolis never obtained proper title to 
the artworks and has no right to possess them 
the court finds that the evidence and testimony of the 
plaintiffs is more credible and persuasive noland said the 
plaintiffs have made a proper showing in all respects for the 
return of the mosaics 
we never had any doubts that the mosaics were unlawfully 
stolen and illegally taken away from cyprus president george 
vassiliou said in a statement issued by the government news agency 
in cyprus 
we always had confidence in the american courts and in that 
sense we can say that the decision of the court comes as no 
surprise but it still fills us with joy because it shows that 
despite difficulties despite adversity justice at the end 
prevails 
michael e sherifis who presented his credentials thursday to 
president bush as the cypriot ambassador to the united states 
called the mosaics an invaluable and integral part of our rich 
cultural heritage 
it will have a great impact on the flow of stolen art around 
the world added june walton a washington attorney for the 
cypriots certainly it will make purchasers think twice before 
they buy stolen art 
ezra h friedlander an indianapolis attorney for ms goldberg 
said his client was very upset 
she feels wronged by the decision he said she doesnt 
think the decision reflected what the evidence presented 
friedlander said an appeal was likely 
goldberg who is coowner of goldberg and feldman fine arts inc 
in carmel bought the mosaics in july 1988 from aydin dikman a 
turk living in germany who claimed he was a former archaeologist 
for the turkish republic of northern cyprus 
the mosaic fragments each roughly 2 feet square were taken 
from a larger work on the ceiling of the panagia kanakarai church 
in northern cyprus in 1979 three years after greek cypriots fled 
the area 
dating back to the year ad 525 the mosaics depict christ as a 
boy the apostles james and matthew and an archangel they are 
among only a few to have survived the rule of the iconoclast 
byzantine emperors of the eighth century who ordered such images 
destroyed 
ms goldberg borrowed 12 million from an indianapolis bank to 
purchase the mosaics she paid 11 million for the art then used 
120000 to pay for the shipping and restoration of the mosaics 
which are stored in an indianapolis bank vault the rest of the 
money was used to cover her expenses 
ms goldberg offered the mosaics last january to the j paul 
getty museum in malibu calif for 20 million the museums 
curator marion true contacted authorities in cyprus who said the 
antiquities had been stolen according to a deposition 
the church and the cypriot government filed suit against ms 
goldberg and her dealership last march the trial began may 30 and 
lasted six days 
during the trial ms goldberg maintained that she bought the 
mosaics in good faith and had tried to determine whether they were 
stolen 
she said the cypriots had not notified interpol customs 
officials in europe or the united states or the international 
foundation for art research that the mosaics were missing 
ms goldberg said she relied solely on ifar a new york 
clearinghouse for information on stolen art which had not 
registered the mosaics as stolen property 
although indiana law does not allow the purchase of stolen 
property under any circumstances ms goldberg and her attorneys 
claimed that swiss law should apply to her case because she had 
purchased the art in switzerland swiss law allows the purchase of 
stolen art if such transactions are made in good faith 
noland however ruled that goldberg is not a goodfaith 
purchaser under swiss law 
the judge said suspicious circumstances surrounding the sale of 
the mosaics should have caused an honest and reasonaably prudent 
purchaser to doubt whether the seller had the capacity to 
convey property rights 
noland also said ms goldberg failed to conduct a reasonable 
inquiry to learn whether the art work was stolen 
noland said in his ruling that further proceedings might be 
needed to determine damages any remaining claims and the transfer 
of the mosaics 
