sales of usmade cars and light trucks sagged 
55 percent in late july and july sales of foreignmade vehicles 
dropped 96 percent compared with the same periods last year 
automakers reported thursday 
despite the big three automakers continued incentive programs 
their car and light truck sales fell 74 percent to an average 
daily rate of 37113 in the july 2131 period from 40096 in late 
july 1988 
latejuly average daily sales for the eight companies producing 
cars and trucks in the united states were 41004 compared with 
43394 in late july last year for the month domestic car and 
truck sales were up 09 an average daily sales pace of 39512 
vehicles compared with 39163 in july 1988 
july sales of imported cars and trucks slipped 96 percent to an 
average daily rate of 31260 vehicles compared with 34590 in july 
1988 
the incentives have had less and less impact said joseph 
phillippi an automotive analyst for shearson lehman hutton inc in 
new york this is a tired market 
for the first seven months of the year domestic car and truck 
sales drooped 39 percent while imported car and truck sales were 
10 percent behind the same period of 1988 
last year was the secondbest sales year in automotive history 
and the latejuly sales rate was slightly above the average for 
that year 
chrysler had the sharpest decline in car sales in late july this 
year a 155 percent drop to a daily rate of 3049 from 3611 a 
year earlier chrysler car sales for the first seven months of 1989 
were down 148 percent 
gm said its latejuly cars sales were down 131 percent to a 
daily rate of 11640 from a 13394aday pace in that time last 
year gm car sales were down 89 percent for the year to date 
ford reported only a 02 percent decline to a daily rate of 
7860 for late july from a rate of 7873 a day in late july of 
1988 car sales for the first seven months of the year were down 
24 percent ford said 
for light trucks gm said sales dropped 8 percent in late july 
and 31 percent for the first seven months chrysler reported a 75 
percent drop for the period and a 08 percent decline for the year 
so far and ford said truck sales were off 3 percent for late july 
and 31 percent for the first seven months 
august sales may pick up phillippi said as shoppers try to 
avoid price increases coming when 1990 models are introduced in the 
fall 
