<TEXT>
roman catholic bishops in this central 
american nation said thursday that because of the political 
violence coupled with labor unrest day by day guatemala is 
falling more deeply into chaos 
the paralyzing of essential services such as mail telegraph 
education and public works and the violent death of a noted 
politician are signs of a profound breakdown of the national 
situation the bishops statement said 
they recalled the bleak days of the early 1980s when political 
slayings by the hundreds and the militarys bloody campaign against 
foes or suspected foes of the government made guatemala an 
international pariah 
remembering the vivid horrors of only a few years ago and in 
fear of returning to those tragic days we turn to god in 
humility the bishops said 
the only civilized way to find just and equitable solutions is 
a frank sincere and respectful dialogue 
about 50000 government employees including teachers and postal 
workers have been on strike for nearly two months for higher 
wages president vinicio cerezo has rejected the demands saying 
the government doesnt have the money 
the strike has closed public schools nationwide and brought mail 
service to a halt daily demonstrations by strikers have snarled 
traffic in the capital and blocked border crossings into mexico 
the strike and the violence that followed it have raised fears 
about the stability of guatemalas fledgling civilian government 
cerezos inauguruation in 1986 came after more than 30 years of 
military or militarydominated rule in guatemala he has survived 
two military coup attempts in 14 months and said recently he was 
the target of a rightwing assassination plot 
in the past few weeks dozens of bombings and bomb threats and 
several killings have hit this nation of about 9 million people 
including the slaying tuesday of danilo barillas a leader in the 
governing christian democratic party 
students sympathizing with the strikers on thursday freed the 
rector of the university of san carlos roderico seguro and about 
50 other university officials after holding them hostage for 24 
hours 
hector adolfo cifuentes the university secretary said none of 
the hostages were harmed 
fourteen public school teachers also ended an 18day hunger 
strike in guatemala citys main plaza outside the national palace 
mario guillermo munoz a strike leader told reporters they 
ended their fast because they had made their point the 14 on 
the verge of collapse were given first aid by red cross volunteers 
and rushed to the hospital 
negotiations continued between strike leaders and government 
officials without cerezo who walked out early wednesday saying he 
was fed up 
education minister ricardo gomez galvez said he was optimistic 
about reaching an accord striking teachers said in a statement 
they might consider going back to work if the government reinstated 
500 fired strikers 
the military on thursday blamed sundays shooting death of 
refugee leader marco juan baltazar on leftist rebels 
baltazar represented repatriated guatemalans on the national 
reconciliation commission set up to discuss an end to the 
27yearold civil war which has displaced tens of thousands of 
people 
