six people pleaded innocent thursday to 
conspiracy and mail fraud charges in a scheme in which 2 million 
in counterfeit coupons from 47 major consumer product companies 
were allegedly distributed nationwide four others indicted by a 
federal grand jury agreed to plead guilty in their home states and 
did not appear at thursdays proceedings officials said 
the defendants face a maximum penalty of five years in prison 
and a 250000 fine on each count all were released on personal 
recognizance bonds 
pleading innocent were james floyd richards of san antonio 
david george rackmill of stamford david keith rees of center 
point connie santos arvidson of boca raton fla peggy joyce 
bunce of deerfield beach fla and margaret mcbrayer goodman of 
kingsport tenn 
the us postal inspectors service uncovered the scheme in 
which coupons for food and other products from the 47 consumer 
product companies allegedly were printed and distributed from texas 
the 24count indictment handed down june 22 said that 
beginning in june 1988 rackmill advertised the coupons in a 
circular mailed to hundreds of people after buying the fake coupons 
from rees who had them printed by richards 
the three allegedly counterfeited 603000 copies of 90 coupons 
issued by the 47 manufacturers the other defendants allegedly 
purchased the coupons from rackmill through the mail according to 
the 24count indictment 
us postal inspector sam prose who worked undercover in the 
case and offered rees coupons for crisco shortening said the 
coupon purchasers participated in the conspiracy by using the 
coupons to obtain large amounts of the products then sell them at 
flea markets 
the coupons were similar to those offered by manufacturers to 
customers in exchange for proofofpurchase seals and were valued 
between 1 and 1089 
agreeing to plead guilty were evelyn christine peoples of 
humphrey ark carol jean juel of fullerton calif yvonne suits 
of cambridge minn and james patrick caprose of newcastle pa 
