<TEXT>
the ways bugs bite sting and pinch are as varied as the insects 
among the most common pestiferous bugs 
mosquitoes with its annoying itch persistent whine and 
syringelike mouth the mosquito is one of mans universal 
scourges more than 2000 species thrive in the united states alone 
most mosquitoes live only a few weeks the average female lays 
more than 100 eggs which can lie dormant for a year in some 
species only the female requires a blood meal males eat pollen 
and nectar 
the female inserts her mouth into the victims skin and secretes 
an anticoagulant ensuring a steady stream of blood bug experts 
believe this anticoagulant causes the itch 
ticks the tick is like a miniature tank and perhaps more 
impregnable with eight legs no antennae or wings few natural 
predators and remarkable abilities to multiply and survive long 
periods without food ticks are considered by entomologists to be 
one of natures most adaptable creatures 
the common american dog tick for example produces 5000 eggs 
at a time each larva must find a host animal to feed upon 
soviet scientists have kept members of one tick species alive for 
14 years without food said robert hall professor of entomology at 
the university of missouri in columbia 
the tick mouth includes a central needle covered with barbs to 
lock it in place like a fishhook once attached the tick exudes a 
gluelike liquid that also helps prevent dislodging a tick 
infected with diseaseproducing organisms can infect the host when 
it feeds 
numerous tick species are found in the united states most of 
which live in woodsy surroundings although they can be transported 
by animals 
flies a plague recorded from biblical times flies fall into 
two categories those that thrive on garbage and waste and those 
that bite thousands of species abound 
flies that breed on filth dont bite or draw blood although 
they can spread disease if they land on an open wound 
male and female biting flies such as the stable fly feed on 
blood they have piercing mouthparts and feed like the mosquito 
most flies lay rapidly hatching eggs in summer a housefly will 
hatch in 12 hours it reaches adulthood in about 10 days 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890803-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
imagine youre surrounded by hordes of 
roaches flies mosquitoes fleas moths beetles and a couple of 
dozen hairy tarantulas devising new ways to kill or repel them 
its a way of life for the scientists at the sc johnson wax 
entomology laboratory the biggest corporate research facility 
devoted to the demise of biting and annoying pests to these 
antibug commandos who helped develop such pioneering products as 
raid and off the battle never ends 
people ask if insects are going to take over the world they 
already have says lab director roger grothaus who has studied 
bugs for more than 25 years 
john randall a senior research scientist at the lab said the 
33 johnson wax entomologists have a healthy respect for the 30 
species of bugs that live there which form a population exceeding 
35 million 
these are high quality insects randall said we think of 
them as precision lab instruments we know exactly how old each 
cockroach is 
the lab consists of several buildings in a suburban neighborhood 
near racine headquarters of johnson wax a privately owned 
consumer products company 
johnson wax does not disclose its bugstudy budget but company 
spokeswoman cynthia georgeson said it allocates more money for 
research and development on urban entomology than all competitors 
combined 
like the members of his staff grothaus is fascinated with bugs 
and the ingenious ways they survive on his desk sit metal 
sculptures of a grasshopper and a scorpion and he drinks from a 
mug illustrated with insect drawings the workers keep a tank of 
hairy tarantulas as lab mascots 
working with entomology lets you stay like a kid grothaus 
said its like being the 8yearold kid who runs around with a 
jar collecting bugs 
in an average week approximately 100000 houseflies and 150000 
mosquitoes are hatched for testing as well as more than 50000 
cockroaches of the american and smaller german varieties 
lab rooms are specially designed for insect habitat their 
temperatures set at 80 degrees with 50 percent relative humidity 
the flea testing area uses an apparatus that the researchers 
call an artificial cat they place fleas in tiny containers 
with cat hair and the fleas pierce a skinlike surface to feed on 
blood 
the researchers scrutinize the insects 365 days a year and even 
though the labs hold racks of containers with thousands of flying 
bugs company officials report few escapees 
i get bit more on the outside than in here randall said 
tests range from freeing houseflies in chemicalfilled cubicles 
to spraying a persons arms with repellent and sticking them into a 
mosquito swarm if a product successfully passes through several 
experiments its tested in homes 
formulas for the insect sprays however must be changed 
routinely because the bugs are so good at adapting to different 
environments grothaus said 
aside from studying ways to kill insects with chemicals the 
center is researching the behavior of insects and ways to modify it 
did you know you can condition a cockroach grothaus said 
now if you could just teach them to leave the house 
one new product devised by johnson wax uses mild electrical 
currents to disrupt the equilibrium of houseflies which then 
crashland on a sticky surface grothaus said the company is 
marketing the product as a safe way to keep kitchens flyfree 
one of the toughest jobs however is finding ways to rout the 
cockroach an insect that arouses particular disgust for grothaus 
i truly dont like them he said i consider them filthy 
grothaus said he thinks the typical household cockroach inspires 
revulsion because it crawls in garbage and then it goes onto your 
plates 
if you see a big bad ugly spider you might be startled 
he said but then the next day you tell people i saw the 
biggest spider but you dont go telling people gee whiz i have 
a house full of cockroaches 
some of the rarer roaches however are treated more fondly at 
the lab 
the scientists keep a container of 4inch madagascar hissing 
cockroaches and randall said theyre viewed more as pets than 
research tools 
these are oh my roaches he said people say oh my 
when they see them 
</TEXT>
