congress should consider reviving regulation 
of the cable tv industry a general accounting office spokesman 
said today after unveiling a survey showing basic cable rates have 
risen 29 percent since deregulation 
i think its time to fully reexamine reregulation john m 
olf jr director of housing and community development issues for 
the gao told a house subcommittee with no competition no 
limited regulation i believe we have a monopoly 
but an industry spokesman said consumers are getting their 
moneys worth from cable tv 
cable subscribers are getting a lot more for their money than 
was the case 16 years ago or even three years ago james p 
mooney president and chief executive officer of the national cable 
television association said in testimony to the energy and 
commerce committees telecommunications and finance subcommittee 
moreover the quality of cable programming something 
impossible to measure statistically but nonetheless real has 
improved markedly over the past couple of years mooney said 
in 1986 mooney said subscribers had an average of 27 channels 
at a cost of 44 cents each while the average rose to 32 in 1988 at 
a cost of 46 cents each 
the monthly cost for the least expensive basic cable service 
increased 29 percent between december 1986 when the cable 
communications policy act of 1984 took effect and october 1988 
according to the gao study 
chairman rep edward markey dmass requested the study to 
help evaluate the effect of deregulated cable rates on consumers 
the monthly fee for the basic service increased from 1123 to 
1448 during the study period the gao said adding that the 
average number of channels increased from 24 to 30 
the report found that the average monthly cost for the most 
popular basic service which may have options such as remote 
control rose 26 percent from 1170 to 1477 
but despite the stiff increases for the two types of basic 
service the gao said the average subscribers monthly bill rose 
only 14 percent from 2158 to 2468 
mooney said that one factor that spurred the increased costs was 
the effort by the relatively young industry to upgrade its plants 
and add channels 
cable companies channeled 246 million into those efforts in 
1986 292 million in 1987 and 417 million in 1988 he said 
mooney also said that the cost of cable rose just 16 percent 
during the first six months of this year while the consumer price 
index rose 3 percent 
this strongly suggests that the postderegulation adjustment 
in cable rates is over he said predicting a more normal 
curve in 1989 and subsequent years 
under deregulation the federal communications commission 
allowed cable television companies which since 1972 had to receive 
permission from local authorities to raise prices for basic 
service to set their own rates 
despite the higher prices the gao study said cable 
subscriptions have risen 15 percent fiftyfive percent of 
households with televisions or 49 million subscribers have cable 
the gao interviewed cable operators as well as federal state 
and local officials to compile its report the agency also randomly 
selected 1950 cable systems nationwide to survey receiving 1451 
usable responses 
