<TEXT>
drexel burnham lambert inc has been ordered to 
turn over thousands of documents in an oklahoma bankruptcy case to 
answer questions about whether its junkbond financing contributed 
to an oil companys downfall 
the unusual chapter 11 proceedings for texas international co 
mark what legal experts believe is the first bankruptcy court 
attack on an investment firm that arranged highinterest financing 
for a company that later went bellyup 
drexel maintains its financing for texas international not only 
was proper but enabled the foundering company to stay in business 
longer than it would have otherwise 
nonetheless the case raises the possibility of similar 
bankruptcy challenges elsewhere if companies that have issued 200 
billion in junk bonds over the last decade dont perform well 
during an economic downturn 
already in 1989 southmark corp with about 800 million in 
drexel junkbond debt has filed for bankruptcy protection from 
creditors the financial concern integrated resources inc recently 
defaulted on close to 800 million in drexel junk debt 
drexel pioneered the widespread use of junk bonds lowrated 
highinterest debt securities for corporate financings mergers 
and takeovers although most major wall street firms now deal in 
the securities 
in 1977 drexel issued its firstever corporate junk bonds for 
oklahoma citybased texas international and restructured 389 
million of the companys longterm debt in the mid1980s 
attorneys for the stockholders committee of texas international 
now claim that terms of the refinancings may have been too severe 
for the struggling energy company 
they also have questioned whether drexel may have misstated 
facts during debt exchange offers in 1985 1986 and 1987 may have 
abused securities laws in conducting the exchange offers or may 
have manipulated the price of company stock around the time of the 
offers 
the attorneys havent said what actions theyre contemplating 
against drexel and havent offered proof for their suspicions 
aired in us bankruptcy court 
no charges against drexel have been filed in the case and texas 
international has said in court documents it has no evidence of 
wrongdoing or harm by drexel 
drexel which faces dozens of unrelated lawsuits based on its 
settlement of federal civil and criminal securities fraud charges 
fought a subpoena issued last december ordering it to produce 
documents about its texas international deals 
in one court document drexel said the companys shareholders 
committee relied on a hodgepodge of vague unsupported 
speculations to justify a search 
not a single fact is recited that could give rise to any 
inference of liability or misconduct on drexels part lawyers 
for the new yorkbased firm said 
but federal bankruptcy law permits such a sweeping inquiry 
what the judge in the texas international case called a fishing 
expedition to determine what caused the bankruptcy and whether 
creditors shareholders or the company were harmed 
drexel already burdened by other lawsuits spun off from its 
past troubles effectively is being forced to defend itself in a 
case where no formal charges have been made the practice could 
affect other wall street firms should bankruptcies increase 
the junk bond issuers are going to look to find someone to sue 
and theyre going to look to whoever the underwriter is 
columbia university law professor mark roe said there will be 
more lender liability cases in a recession of which this might be 
a portion 
according to documents filed in bankruptcy court in oklahoma 
city drexel holds 2176 million of the 166 million in debt 
comprising most of the claims against texas international 
drexel also owns an unspecified amount of stock in the company 
some of which was issued to cover the debt was responsible for 
creating the market for texas international stock on the pacific 
stock exchange and was the companys financial adviser 
it seems to us that there a number of questions relative to 
drexels conflict of interest holding of securities potential 
different agenda that should be investigated charles e 
ramsey jr texas internationals courtappointed bankruptcy 
examiner testified at a may 18 hearing on whether the inquiry was 
necessary 
the shareholders committee also used in its argument drexels 
recent agreement to pay 650 million and plead guilty to six 
felonies to settle securities and exchange commission fraud charges 
stemming from the governments insidertrading crackdown 
texas internationals case includes many prominent drexel 
players including michael milken the former drexel junkbond 
financier indicted earlier this year on unrelated charges 
milwaukee attorney benjamin waisbren who represents texas 
international shareholders told us bankruptcy judge richard 
bohanan that drexel should be investigated partly because the 
pattern of activity in the sec suit coincided with the texas 
international refinancings 
texas international was not mentioned in the secs wideranging 
complaint against drexel last september 
waisbren said in court that the three drexelarranged exchange 
offers included new debt that was to be serviced by issuing stock 
until the company could pay cash 
but he said the offers were not feasible because the value 
of the stock was inadequate to service the debt company documents 
place the shortfall at 63 million in 1986 and 76 million in 1987 
rejecting drexels challenges bohanan in june ordered drexel to 
turn over documents from its highyield bond division in beverly 
hills calif and to provide access to employees who worked with 
texas international from 1985 through 1988 
texas international an oil and gas production and exploration 
company with operations in egypt malaysia and the united states 
has lost more than 384 million since 1981 already loaded with 
debt entering the 1980s the company was hoping for an oil price 
rise 
but the industry slumped and texas international either had to 
renegotiate debt payments or declare bankruptcy company officials 
said drexel was paid 6075 million in fees for the exchanges 
records show 
