<TEXT>
a rash of defaults among companies that have 
borrowed heavily by selling highyield debt securities is raising 
fear that a recession could wallop the nations 200 billion market 
in socalled junk bonds 
nonetheless the people who deal in junk bonds say a recession 
wont be disastrous and some economists agree 
youre heading toward at best an economic slowdown at worst a 
recession said david wyss senior economist with drimcgrawhill 
inc in lexington mass under those conditions youre going to 
get defaults 
in a recent study wyss concluded that a recession would trigger 
more junk bond defaults but that high returns would easily offset 
losses if bond buyers keep diversified portfolios 
junk bonds are so named because they pay high rates of interest 
to compensate for their low or nonexistent credit rating junk 
bonds have become an enormously popular financing technique for the 
growth of small companies and to raise money for debtfinanced 
takeovers known as leveraged buyouts 
this year junk bond industry officials say about 3 billion in 
junk bonds have stopped paying interest or are undergoing a 
restructuring as part of overhauls by struggling companies 
integrated resources inc which has 798 million in junk debt 
underwritten by drexel burnham lambert inc defaulted in june 
southmark inc with 757 million in oustanding drexel junk debt 
entered bankruptcy court in midjuly 
sci television has defaulted on 475 million in junk while the 
thrifts gibraltar financial corp and western savings amp loan 
association defaulted on interest or principal payments on more 
than 100 million each 
but integrated and southmark dont reflect peril junk backers 
say because the financial concerns were hard hit by changes in 
federal tax laws in 1986 they say more defaults indicate only that 
the junk market has grown 
drexel the pioneer of the junk bond market says that 125 
billion or 66 percent of the total 197 billion in bonds issued 
since 1977 have defaulted that converts to an annual average 
default rate of 24 percent 
according to drexel figures 23 percent of junk bond defaults to 
date were by energy companies which have suffered because of oil 
price declines 9 percent were by public service company of new 
hampshire which has been struggling because of costs associated 
with a nuclear plant and 8 percent were in the steel industry 
which has lost to foreign competition 
historically speaking recessions have had very little impact 
on highyield bond default rates said joe bencivenga 
codirector of research for drexels highyield bond department in 
beverly hills calif 
a report by moodys investors service in july found that 33 
percent of junk bond issuers defaulted on longterm bonds each year 
between 1970 and 1988 over a 10year period the rate was 17 
percent moodys put the annual default rate for investmentgrade 
bonds at 006 percent 
in june a harvard business school study alarmed the market by 
reporting that 293 percent of new junk bond issues defaulted from 
1979 to 1988 
on capitol hill a compromise bill to bail out the nations 
savings and loans would prevent thrifts from using their deposits 
to invest in junk bonds the concern is that the thrifts which own 
more than 14 billion in the bonds shouldnt risk customer 
deposits 
a general accounting office report in march concluded that 
highyield bonds did not contribute to the thrift crisis but it 
said investing in the securities remains risky 
the highyield bond market in its present size and form has 
not been tested by a recession the report stated a severe 
economic downturn might increase bond defaults especially for 
those companies issuing bonds as part of leveraged buyouts 
</TEXT>
