<TEXT>
opec nations continued to pump oil at a 
robust rate in july despite promises to curtail their crude output 
according to estimates released thursday 
the international energy agency said in its monthly oil market 
report that the 13nation organization of petroleum exporting 
countries produced about 213 million barrels a day last month the 
same as in june those were the highest levels so far this year 
the cartel set a production ceiling of 195 million barrels a 
day for the last half of the year in an effort to keep a firm grip 
on output and control prices opec set 18 a barrel as a target 
price for the seven types of crudes that it monitors 
but production has remained strong and prices have weakened 
west texas intermediate the american benchmark crude which 
normally sells at about 2 above opecmonitored crudes has fallen 
nearly 6 since april when it sold at more than 24 a barrel after 
stabilizing in the 1920 range for several weeks this spring and 
summer prices recently slipped to the 18 level 
analysts see few signs that nations ignoring their new supply 
quotas will cut back and their actions may spur others to cheat as 
well opec ministers raised their production ceiling in june from 
185 million barrels a day in the first half of the year to 195 
million 
the situation is becoming more dangerous for opec said 
fergus macleod analyst at barclays de zoete wedd in london 
opecs eightmember monitoring panel will meet in geneva on 
sept 23 to take a look at the market and decide whether to boost 
the production cap to 20 million barrels a day in the final three 
months of the year 
the meeting was officially scheduled for just the eight 
committee members but ministers of the other five member nations 
also were expected to attend 
macleod said chances were diminishing that the cartel would lift 
its output ceiling in the last quarter because of a slowdown in 
demand for opec oil 
figures supplied by the international energy agency put demand 
for opec oil in the second half of this year at about 213 million 
barrels a day some 400000 barrels above earlier estimates 
demand however is expected to tumble to about 207 million 
barrels a day in the januaryjune period of 1990 analysts said 
the opec nations sharply trimmed their production starting late 
last year year to comply with an output accord fashioned in 
november to boost prices their cutbacks combined with accidents 
in oilproducing regions like the north sea and perceptions of 
supply problems due to the exxon oil spill in alaska helped kick 
prices up to unexpected levels last spring 
prices have eased recently however 
the average price of seven major crude brands monitored by opec 
was 1658 in the last week of july under the 18 target but it 
was well above the average price of 1234 recorded at the end of 
last november 
to meet the present target a number of countries would have had 
to cut their output but the energy agencys figures indicate that 
hasnt happened 
kuwait for example produced an estimated 16 million barrels a 
day in july above its opec quota of 11 million barrels a day 
output for the united arab emirates a persistent cheater was 
about 18 million barrels a day well over its quota of 1 million 
barrels 
nigerias output was estimated at 16 million barrels a day 
higher than its quota of 14 million barrels 
saudia arabia the worlds no 1 oil exporter pumped 47 
million barrels a day last month about the same as its quota 
iraq and iran were recorded at their quota levels of 28 million 
barrels a day as was venezuela at 17 million barrels the energy 
agency reported 
the other opec members produced near their targets indonesia 
12 million barrels ecuador 300000 barrels algeria 700000 
barrels qatar 400000 barrels libya 11 million barrels and 
gabon 200000 barrels 
opec recently acknowledged that its members supplied more crude 
to the world market in june than allowed under their production 
agreement 
opec differs from other analysts in the way it measures 
adherence to its production agreements it calculates a nations 
quota by figuring crude production and then subtracting or adding 
the amount of oil put into or drawn out of stocks 
the international energy agency is part of the organization for 
economic cooperation and development which is made up of 24 
western nations including the united states japan france and 
west germany 
</TEXT>
