<DOCNO> AP890803-0301 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
making the soviet ruble into a useful world 
currency will require farreaching reforms of the soviet economic 
system according to a report to moscow by a panel of soviets and 
westerners 
the 60page report released thursday was sought by soviet 
officials who are searching for ways to bring their rigid 
unproductive economy into the modern world of trade and finance 
i hope that this is something that is to be carefully looked 
at we hope to distribute it widely in the soviet union vladimir 
popov one of the soviet participants said in a telephone 
interview 
the report was released at the geonomics institute think tank in 
middlebury vt the meeting place for the panel which was made up 
of scholars from the united states canada france and the soviet 
union 
because the ruble cannot be freely exchanged for dollars yen 
marks and other western currencies it has virtually no value 
outside the soviet union 
making the ruble convertible would permit expanded trade with 
the west and impose a market discipline on inefficient soviet 
enterprises in keeping with the perestroika campaign of soviet 
president mikhail gorbachev 
it also would encourage more foreign investment in the soviet 
union leading to a transfer of technology from the west western 
business executives favor it because they feel it would open a huge 
untapped market for their goods and services 
the panel proposed a fivestep plan for achieving full 
convertibility of the ruble possibly by as early as the year 2000 
but it noted that the obstacles to even a partial 
convertibility of the ruble are daunting it could trigger 
spiraling inflation cause shortages throw people out of work and 
exacerbate differences between rich and poor the panel said 
although the soviet council of foreign ministers last december 
ordered up a plan for partial convertibility of the ruble 
beginning with a 50 percent devaluation this coming jan 1 many 
observers believe the concept could run afoul of internal politics 
id say that the odds of a plan that would get the soviet 
union to meaningful convertibility being adopted are probably 
5050 in the foreseeable future said josef c brada an arizona 
state university professor who led the vermont panel 
as a first step toward convertibility the panel said hard 
western currencies should be sold to the highest bidding state 
enterprise instead of allocated by central planners as is 
currently done after that it said the auction should be 
broadened to a wider range of state enterprises 
in a third phase cooperatives private enterprises and 
sovietwestern joint ventures should be allowed to bid for hard 
currencies in an open auction which gradually would turn into a 
genuine foreignexchange market the panel said 
households would be allowed to own foreign currencies in a 
fourth phase although the government could maintain a twotier 
exchange rate finally foreigners would be given the right to 
exchange rubles freely 
the official exchange rate for the ruble is about 160 but the 
black market rate ranges from 40 cents to as little as 9 cents to 
the ruble 
making the ruble convertible would destroy the soviet pricing 
system under which industrial goods and raw materials are cheap 
and consumer goods are expensive 
entrepreneurs could exploit the discrepancy by selling cheap 
soviet oil to the united states at a huge markup for example 
using the dollars to buy japanese tape recorders and selling the 
tape recorders in the soviet union at another huge markup 
such trades would leave soviets short of oil and quickly put the 
soviet tape recorder factories out of business 
to prevent that the panel favors controls on trade that 
gradually would be phased out as soviet pricing came into line with 
world pricing 
many people have hoards of rubles with nothing to spend them on 
if they were allowed to exchange them for dollars a giant 
reservoir of money would be opened and inflation would soar 
the soviet and western participants disagreed on several points 
popov said he favored heavy borrowing from the west to ease the 
pain of a five to sevenyear transition to a market economy 
brada the group leader said that would lead to a debt crunch like 
polands 
brada said he favored wiping out the existing ruble hoards by 
issuing a new ruble something that josef stalin did in 1947 popov 
said such a step would be unpopular and rumors of it would trigger 
a run on stores as people spent their soontobeworthless currency 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

