<TEXT>
cigna reported thursday a 39 percent 
increase in secondquarter earnings despite a decrease of 68 
percent in the insurance companys operating profits on property 
and casualty underwriting 
wilson h taylor president and chief executive officer said 
the decrease which totaled 106 million for the first half of the 
year was caused by generally inadequate pricing in the 
property and casualty market 
he warned the situation could worsen because there are no 
clear signs that the underwriting cycles decline has ended 
for the second quarter net income totaled 144 million or 
177 a share on revenue of 38 billion for the same period in 
1988 the company reported income of 1388 million or 165 a 
share on revenue of 36 billion 
for the first six months of 1989 the company reported income of 
2295 million or 280 a share on revenue of 75 billion the 
figures represent a 57 increase over the 2171 million or 25 
cents a share from last years first half 
the largest quarterly increase in operating profit was in 
investment gains with 174 million reported for the past quarter 
a 241 percent increase over the 72 million reported last year 
the property and casualty operations had operating income of 
266 million in the second quarter down 68 percent from the 839 
million reported a year ago 
