<DOCNO> AP890803-0331 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
lincoln savings amp loan used accounting 
gimmickry to inflate its profits a private accounting firm 
said in a report released thursday as regulators put the insolvent 
thrift in receivership 
seldom in our experience as accountants have we encountered a 
more egregious example of the misapplication of generally accepted 
accounting principles kenneth leventhal amp co said in the report 
federal regulators who seized the irvinebased thrift in april 
placed lincoln in receivership thursday chartering a new federal 
mutual association to run it under the name lincoln savings amp loan 
association fa 
the action helps prevent its former parent phoenixbased 
american continental corp from making claims on lincolns 408 
billion in assets in april american continental filed for 
reorganzation under federal bankruptcy laws 
lincoln remained open throughout its ordeal and depositors will 
be able to continue their business with lincoln as usual federal 
home loan bank board chairman danny wall said thursday 
a federal audit found lincoln had a negative net worth of 631 
million as of june 30 and state officials said last week that 
lincoln was 906 million in the hole some analysts and regulators 
have estimated the total loss to the government may top 2 billion 
which would make lincoln the costliest thrift collapse ever 
american continental has been criticized for using lincolns 
federally insured deposits for junk bond and other nontraditional 
investments regulators are investigating whether lincoln and 
american continental used improper transfers of funds and 
accounting methods to make the unit look healthier than it was 
thursdays 10page report by leventhal amp co which examined 15 
real estate transactions at lincoln stemmed from a wider special 
examination ordered by the federal home loan bank board in 1988 
bank board spokesman bill fulwider said 
in order to boost earnings lincoln entered into noneconomic 
transactions and turned to accounting gimmickry the july 14 
report to the bank board said 
leventhal acknowledged that its report was based on limited 
information but said they believed it was adequate to support its 
findings 
lincoln was manufacturing profits the report concluded 
in phoenix american continental attorney marilyn fried said she 
had not seen the report and could not comment on its specifics but 
she denied that lincoln and american continental had used improper 
accounting techniques saying their books had been audited by major 
accounting firms 
she accused regulators of vastly overstating lincolns losses 
noting that officials had put the thrifts net worth at 112 
million as of dec 31 and a stillsolvent 20 million even when it 
was seized in april 
lincoln was placed in the joint conservatorship of the federal 
savings and loan insurance corp and federal deposit insurance 
corp on april 14 but until thursday it was still technically 
owned by american continental said fulwider 
fulwider described the receivership as a further step toward 
final resolution but said an immediate sale or liquidation of 
lincoln was not in sight 
</TEXT>
